===Кірме сөздер===

In a 1934 book entitled ''Die Germanismen des Litauischen. Teil I: Die deutschen Lehnwörter im Litauischen'', K. Alminauskis found 2,770 loan words, of which about 130 were of uncertain origin. The majority of the loan words were found to have been derived from the [[Polish language|Polish]], [[Belarussian language|Belarussian]], and [[German language|German]] languages, with some evidence that these languages all acquired the words from contacts and trade with [[Prussia]] during the era of the [[Grand Duchy of Lithuania]].<ref>[http://cejsh.icm.edu.pl/cejsh/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?07PLAAAA02144515  Ways of Germanisms into Lithuanian].  N. Cepiene,  Acta Baltico-Slavica, 2006</ref> Loan words comprised about 20% of the vocabulary used in the first book printed in the Lithuanian language in 1547, [[Martynas Mažvydas]]'s  ''[[Catechism]]''.<ref>[http://pirmojiknyga.mch.mii.lt/Leidiniai/History.en.htm Martynas Mažvydas' Language]. [[Zigmas Zinkevičius]], 1996. Accessed [[October 26]], 2007.</ref> The majority of loan words in the 20th century arrived from the [[Russian language]].<ref>[http://cejsh.icm.edu.pl/cejsh/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?07PLAAAA02154540  Slavic loanwords in the northern sub-dialect of the southern part of west high Lithuanian]. V. Sakalauskiene, Acta Baltico-Slavica 2006. Accessed [[October 26]], 2007.</ref> Towards the end of the 20th century a number of [[English language]] words and expressions entered the spoken vernacular of city dwellers, especially the younger ones.<ref>[http://www.lituanus.org/1994_2/94_2_01.htm The Anglicization of Lithuanian]. Antanas Kilmas, [[Lituanus]], Summer 1994. Accessed [[October 26]], 2007.</ref>

The Lithuanian government has an established language policy, which encourages the development of equivalent vocabulary to replace loan words.<ref>[http://64.233.167.104/search?q=cache:fb3dO8zUfjkJ:www.vlkk.lt/files/language_policy_guidelines.doc+lithuanian+loanwords&hl=en&ct=clnk&cd=29&gl=us&lr=lang_en|lang_de  State Language Policy Guidelines 2003–2008]. [[Seimas]] of Lithuania, 2003. Accessed [[October 26]], 2007.</ref>

